Does your baby take a pacifier? Did he take it easily or did you have to work for it? What shape/brand works best for your baby?⁣
⁣
𝗦𝗼𝗺𝗲 𝗰𝗼𝗺𝗺𝗼𝗻 𝗾𝘂𝗲𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻𝘀 𝗜 𝗴𝗲𝘁 𝗮𝗯𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗽𝗮𝗰𝗶𝗳𝗶𝗲𝗿𝘀: ⁣
⁣
𝗦𝗵𝗼𝘂𝗹𝗱 𝗺𝘆 𝗯𝗮𝗯𝘆 𝘂𝘀𝗲 𝗮 𝗽𝗮𝗰𝗶𝗳𝗶𝗲𝗿?⁣
It’s up to you and your little one! 💕⁣
⁣
Here are reasons I love the pacifier:⁣
✅Releases endorphins⁣
✅Promotes relaxation⁣
✅Decreases the risk of SIDS⁣
✅ Soothes symptoms of reflux⁣
⁣
𝗜'𝗺 𝗮 𝗻𝘂𝗿𝘀𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗺𝗼𝗺, 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗺𝘆 𝗯𝗮𝗯𝘆 𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗹𝗹 𝗵𝗮𝘃𝗲 𝗮 𝗽𝗮𝗰𝗶𝗳𝗶𝗲𝗿? 𝗪𝗵𝗲𝗻?⁣
Absolutely! 💗 You will always want to respond to hunger cues with a feeding, but a pacifier IS acceptable, even for breastfed babies. Research shows that nursing moms who introduce a pacifier early are JUST as successful with nursing as those who wait. (𝘛𝘩𝘪𝘴 𝘳𝘦𝘴𝘦𝘢𝘳𝘤𝘩 𝘪𝘴 𝘭𝘪𝘯𝘬𝘦𝘥 𝘪𝘯 𝘴𝘵𝘰𝘳𝘪𝘦𝘴 𝘢𝘯𝘥 𝘮𝘺 "𝘐𝘯𝘵𝘳𝘰𝘥𝘶𝘤𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘢 𝘗𝘢𝘤𝘪𝘧𝘪𝘦𝘳" 𝘣𝘭𝘰𝘨.) ⁣
⁣
𝗪𝗵𝗮𝘁 𝗶𝗳 𝗺𝘆 𝗯𝗮𝗯𝘆 𝗴𝗮𝗴𝘀 𝗼𝗿 𝗽𝘂𝘀𝗵𝗲𝘀 𝗶𝘁 𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵 𝗵𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼𝗻𝗴𝘂𝗲? 𝗗𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝘀 𝗺𝗲𝗮𝗻 𝘀𝗵𝗲 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀𝗻’𝘁 𝘄𝗮𝗻𝘁 𝗶𝘁?⁣
These are actually reflexes, so probably not. See the tips in this video to help!⁣
⁣
𝗜𝗳 𝗺𝘆 𝗯𝗮𝗯𝘆 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀𝗻’𝘁 𝘁𝗮𝗸𝗲 𝗮 𝗽𝗮𝗰𝗶𝗳𝗶𝗲𝗿, 𝘀𝗵𝗼𝘂𝗹𝗱 𝗜 𝗸𝗲𝗲𝗽 𝗼𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗶𝘁? ⁣
For babies younger than 12 weeks, you can offer different shapes and brands a few times each day. Use the techniques shown in this video about 30 minutes after a feeding and when baby is calm. ⁣
*️⃣Most won’t accept it after 10-12 weeks if they haven’t accepted it prior. ⁣
⁣
𝗜𝘀 𝗮 𝗽𝗮𝗰𝗶𝗳𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝗿𝗲𝗾𝘂𝗶𝗿𝗲𝗱 𝗳𝗼𝗿 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗧𝗮𝗸𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗖𝗮𝗿𝗮 𝗕𝗮𝗯𝗶𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀? ⁣
Although pacifiers are a helpful tool in the newborn stage, they are NOT a requirement for any of my classes. You can have a great little sleeper with, or without, a pacifier. (𝘓𝘪𝘯𝘬 𝘵𝘰 𝘤𝘭𝘢𝘴𝘴𝘦𝘴 𝘪𝘯 𝘮𝘺 𝘣𝘪𝘰!) 😊⁣
⁣
What if the pacifier becomes an issue and makes our nights and naps more difficult?⁣
I have a blog for you with tips and videos to help. 😉 (𝘚𝘦𝘦 𝘭𝘪𝘯𝘬 𝘪𝘯 𝘣𝘪𝘰 𝘧𝘰𝘳 𝘵𝘩𝘦 𝘣𝘭𝘰𝘨 𝘰𝘳 𝘵𝘰𝘥𝘢𝘺’𝘴 𝘴𝘵𝘰𝘳𝘪𝘦𝘴!) ⁣

node.text:
Did you know there can be another regression at 18 months?! Let's talk about it!⁣
⁣
At this age, your toddler is meeting 𝗠𝗔𝗦𝗦𝗜𝗩𝗘 developmental milestones!🥳🎉 We know with 𝗱𝗲𝘃𝗲𝗹𝗼𝗽𝗺𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗹 𝗽𝗿𝗼𝗴𝗿𝗲𝘀𝘀𝗶𝗼𝗻𝘀, we can often see 𝘀𝗹𝗲𝗲𝗽 𝗿𝗲𝗴𝗿𝗲𝘀𝘀𝗶𝗼𝗻𝘀! ⁣
⁣
👏He may be starting to run or climb, follow one-step commands, imitate household tasks, and name many familiar objects.⁣
👏She is gaining a new understanding of cause and effect, her desire for independence is increasing, and she's developing greater awareness of her ability to make decisions.⁣
⁣
Your kiddo is beginning to think: "Wait, I can 𝗰𝗵𝗼𝗼𝘀𝗲 what I do... Maybe I don't 𝘸𝘢𝘯𝘵 to sleep."⁣
⁣
𝗦𝗼, 𝗵𝗼𝘄 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝘆𝗼𝘂 𝗵𝗲𝗹𝗽 𝗱𝘂𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝘀 𝘀𝗹𝗲𝗲𝗽 𝗿𝗲𝗴𝗿𝗲𝘀𝘀𝗶𝗼𝗻?⁣
⁣
1️⃣𝗥𝗲𝗺𝗲𝗺𝗯𝗲𝗿: 𝗧𝗼𝗱𝗱𝗹𝗲𝗿𝘀 𝙨𝙩𝙞𝙡𝙡 𝗻𝗲𝗲𝗱 𝘀𝗹𝗲𝗲𝗽! Even if he can now "choose" not to sleep — hold onto that nap. If he refuses to sleep during nap time or takes a short nap, move bedtime earlier!⁣
⁣
2️⃣𝗙𝗶𝗹𝗹 𝘂𝗽 𝘁𝗵𝗮𝘁 “𝘁𝗶𝗿𝗲𝗱 𝘁𝗮𝗻𝗸." Plan for lots of active play (I know this is tough right now.). Most 18-month-olds will need about 5-6 hours of awake time prior to nap time. Wake your little one by 3 pm (3:30 pm at the latest) to maintain a 7-8 pm bedtime.⁣
⁣
3️⃣𝗔𝗹𝗹𝗼𝘄 𝗶𝗻𝗱𝗲𝗽𝗲𝗻𝗱𝗲𝗻𝗰𝗲! Empower her with choices like which jammies to wear, which books to read, or which parent gets to rock her before bed.⁣
⁣
4️⃣𝗨𝗻𝗱𝗲𝗿𝘀𝘁𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗵𝗼𝘄 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗯𝗮𝗯𝘆 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗸𝘀. Now that he understands his actions make an impact on you, we need to be very careful about how we react to tough moments. See today’s stories for more.⁣
⁣
5️⃣𝗕𝗲 𝗖𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗲𝗻𝘁. This regression may be tough for a few days, but inconsistency can create a long-term struggle. Avoid starting new habits that you don’t want to maintain.⁣
⁣
6️⃣𝗛𝗮𝘃𝗲 𝗮 𝗽𝗹𝗮𝗻. If your nights and naps are rough beyond just a few days, I have a class for you! “The ABC’s of Sleep” will give you a step-by-step plan to restful nights and solid naps through ALL regressions. ⁣
⁣
Now, who wants to share their favorite part about this stage?

Have you ever experienced this? Was disrupted sleep your first sign of an ear infection? ⁣
⁣
Why does this happen? ⁣
➡️ Well, when babies lay flat it increases pressure on the eardrum. If it’s infected, it can be very painful! 😢 This pain can understandably cause your little one to wake up at night (even if she is typically a great sleeper.) ⁣
⁣
🎉 This is one AMAZING benefit to having a great, sleeper!! Those rough nights can alert you to something needing attention. ⁣
⁣
*️⃣ Now, a rough night does not always mean your baby has an ear infection. Just know that if your nights are ALL OF A SUDDEN rough, it's worth exploring the possibility! ⁣
⁣
"But Cara, what if our nights are always rough??"⁣
⁣
Don't worry! I have a class that can help you! 💕 Just click the link in the bio and select your baby’s age. Each class is taught from the science of a nurse and the heart of a mama and will meet your baby right where he or she is at developmentally!

Signs it’s time to drop from 2️⃣ naps to 1️⃣…⁣
⁣
🌟 Baby is *𝗧𝗬𝗣𝗜𝗖𝗔𝗟𝗟𝗬* 𝟭𝟯-𝟭𝟴 𝗺𝗼𝗻𝘁𝗵𝘀 old 𝗔𝗡𝗗 you’re seeing one or more of these signs 𝗖𝗢𝗡𝗦𝗜𝗦𝗧𝗘𝗡𝗧𝗟𝗬: ⁣
⁣
➡️Baby is consistently struggling to fall asleep or stay asleep at nap time.⁣
➡️The 2nd nap of the day is ending so late it’s consistently pushing bedtime after 8pm.⁣
➡️Night wakings or early morning wakings suddenly and consistently appear.⁣
⁣
𝗖𝗼𝗺𝗺𝗼𝗻 𝗤𝘂𝗲𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻: ⁣
BUT…what if I am seeing some of these signs occasionally? 🤔 What do you recommend?⁣
⁣
𝗔𝗻𝘀𝘄𝗲𝗿: ⁣
➡️ Stay on 2 naps until you are 𝗖𝗢𝗡𝗦𝗜𝗦𝗧𝗘𝗡𝗧𝗟𝗬 seeing these signs!⁣
⁣
𝗛𝗼𝘄? ⁣
➡️ Add a bit more time between wake windows.⁣
⁣
𝗧𝗿𝘆 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝘀: ⁣
🔸Wake ⁣
3.5-3.75 hours⁣
🔸Nap 1 ⁣
3.75-4 hours⁣
🔸Nap 2⁣
3.75-4 hours ⁣
🔸Bedtime⁣
⁣
𝗧𝗵𝗶𝘀 𝗰𝗼𝘂𝗹𝗱 𝗹𝗼𝗼𝗸 𝗹𝗶𝗸𝗲:⁣
🔸Wake- 6:30am ⁣
🔸Nap 1- 10:00-11:30am⁣
🔸Nap 2- 3:15-4:15pm⁣
🔸Bedtime- 8:00pm⁣
⁣
𝗦𝗽𝗲𝗰𝗶𝗮𝗹 𝗻𝗼𝘁𝗲: ⁣
Depending on your schedule, this may push bedtime a bit past 8 pm. HOWEVER, it may be just the answer you need to help you stay on 2 naps for just a few weeks longer until your little one is truly ready! This will make the transition so much easier! 🙌🏼🎉⁣
⁣
Are you thinking about the 2 to 1 nap transition? Have you already transitioned? If so, how old was your little one? Any advice?

Babyproofing 101... Pull up a chair, we're getting practical! 🙌⁣
⁣
“𝙒𝙝𝙚𝙣 𝙙𝙤 𝙄 𝙨𝙩𝙖𝙧𝙩 𝙩𝙝𝙞𝙣𝙠𝙞𝙣𝙜 𝙖𝙗𝙤𝙪𝙩 𝙩𝙝𝙞𝙨?”⁣
🔹Start BEFORE your baby learns to crawl. (Or today... whichever comes first.😉)⁣
⁣
“𝙃𝙤𝙬 𝙙𝙤 𝙄 𝙚𝙫𝙚𝙣 𝙗𝙚𝙜𝙞𝙣?”⁣
🔹Start by getting on your hands and knees —get down on your little one's level. Look and see what your baby can see.⁣
⁣
“𝙒𝙝𝙖𝙩 𝙖𝙧𝙚 𝙩𝙝𝙞𝙣𝙜𝙨 𝙩𝙤 𝙘𝙤𝙣𝙨𝙞𝙙𝙚𝙧?” ⁣
🔹Cover outlets to prevent little fingers/objects from being inserted.⁣
🔹Install baby gates at the top and bottom of stairs. Practice shutting it each and every time you walk through it.⁣
🔹Install a latch on your toilet seat. Baby heads are heavy and falling in the toilet is a drowning risk. (I know this sounds awful, but I have to tell you. It saves lives.)⁣
🔹Anchor heavy furniture to the wall. Littles love to crawl into dresser drawers, and they tip easily.⁣
🔹Move plastic bags, cleaning supplies, medications, and chemicals out of reach or into a locked cabinet.⁣
🔹Set your hot water heater to max out at 120 degrees to help prevent scalding.⁣
🔹If you have a backyard pool, have MANY layers of protection including door alarms and self-closing gates.⁣
⁣
What other tips do you have?⁣ Tag a new parent who may benefit! 💕⁣
⁣
✨ Check out my Amazon store to see some of my favorite babyproofing products! (Link in stories.)⁣ Is there anything I should add??

node.text:
“Sleepy cues” are how your baby speaks to you.⁣
⁣
It’s how she shows you when: ⁣
👉She’s getting tired. ⁣
👉She needs a nap…now! ⁣
👉She’s getting overtired. ⁣
⁣
GOAL ➡️ Aim for a full wake window without pushing him to overtired! ⁣
⁣
Overtired babies often struggle with falling asleep AND staying asleep. An overtired newborn can even appear to have colic-like symptoms!⁣😱😱😱⁣ ⁣
⁣
❤️Please note: Not all babies will demonstrate every sleepy cue noted in this graphic. Look for one or more. ⁣
In my newborn class, I’ll teach you exactly what to DO when you see these cues! ♥️⁣
⁣
Have an older baby and sleep is a struggle? Just click the link in the bio. ⁣
⁣
Be sure to see today’s stories to see babies communicating these sleepy cues to their parents! Tag me in your stories and show me how your baby tells you it’s nap time! ⁣
⁣
What sleepy cues does your baby use to tell you it’s nap time or bedtime? Have you ever experienced an “overtired” baby? How did you handle it? Anyone think you had a colicky baby, but after the newborn class you learned overtiredness was the culprit?

node.text:
At about 6 months, babies begin to understand that objects and people STILL exist, even when they can’t see them anymore. This is called object permanence and is the cause of separation anxiety. ⁣
⁣
As parents, it's our job to reinforce that "Mommy (or Daddy) always comes back"… even when baby can't see you. ⁣
⁣
You are ALREADY teaching this important lesson quite often. Let me give you some examples: ⁣
⁣
👉 When you set baby in the bouncer to run to the bathroom and return a minute later. ⁣
👉 When you hand baby off to another caregiver so you can shower, and return when you're finished. ⁣
👉 When you drop your little one off at daycare and come back at the end of the day. ⁣
⁣
Each of these everyday situations says to your baby, "See! I'll ALWAYS come back for you!" ⁣
⁣
⭐ Creating and maintaining predictable routines around sleep are GREAT ways to show your baby that parents always come back, and that a little bit of safe separation doesn't have to be scary. ⭐️ ⁣
⁣
If separation anxiety is starting to affect your baby’s sleep, here are a few key tips to help you through it: ⁣
🔑 𝗠𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗯𝗲𝗱𝘁𝗶𝗺𝗲 𝗿𝗼𝘂𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗲. A familiar routine provides security and predictability.⁣ ⁣
🔑 𝗕𝗲 𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗺 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗿𝗲𝗮𝘀𝘀𝘂𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗴: Babies read our body language. Let them know that they are safe and you are not upset by this brief separation. They mirror our emotions. ⁣
🔑 𝗗𝗼𝗻'𝘁 𝗮𝗱𝗱 𝗻𝗲𝘄 𝗵𝗮𝗯𝗶𝘁𝘀. Predictable boundaries around sleep help babies feel safe. Adding new interventions may become long-term obstacles. (This is how a developmental stride becomes a sleep regression!)⁣
🔑 𝗛𝗮𝘃𝗲 𝗮 𝗽𝗹𝗮𝗻. If nights and naps become rough, have a plan to reassure your little one that mommy (or daddy) always comes back, even when your baby is in the crib. If you need a plan to follow, my online class “The ABC’s of Sleep” is here to help! Let me teach you how to customize a sleep plan for your little one while reminding him that you are always there for him. (Link in bio)⁣
⁣
At what age did you start to see separation anxiety? Any tips for handling it? Have you started saying “Mommy always comes back”? Does it help? (Be sure to see stories!)

I know! I know, it sounds crazy but let me explain!⁣
⁣
⭐️𝗘𝘅𝗰𝗲𝗲𝗱𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗧𝗪𝗢 𝗵𝗼𝘂𝗿𝘀 𝗳𝗼𝗿 𝗮 𝗻𝗮𝗽 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗺𝗮𝗸𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴𝘀 𝘁𝗿𝗶𝗰𝗸𝘆 𝗳𝗼𝗿 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗼𝗳 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗱𝗮𝘆 (𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗻𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁.)⁣
⁣
These extra-long naps can cause: ⁣
👉 𝗠𝗼𝗿𝗲 𝗻𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝘄𝗮𝗸𝗶𝗻𝗴𝘀: Baby may have fulfilled his sleep needs during the day.⁣ We need good awake time between naps in order to have those consolidated nights and good, restorative night sleep.⁣
👉 𝗜𝗻𝘀𝘂𝗳𝗳𝗶𝗰𝗶𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗱𝗮𝘆𝘁𝗶𝗺𝗲 𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗼𝗿𝗶𝗲𝘀: We need to offer feedings about every 2.5-3.5 hours all day long. If naps extend too long, it can impede on caloric intake. (Cue unnecessary night feedings! 🤦🏼‍♀️)⁣
👉 𝗠𝗲𝘀𝘀𝘆 𝗻𝗮𝗽 𝘀𝗰𝗵𝗲𝗱𝘂𝗹𝗲: By allowing longer naps, there simply won't be enough time to fit in the other necessary nap(s) before bedtime. This can cause long wake windows prior to bedtime! (Think: cranky little one!)⁣
👉 𝗟𝗮𝘁𝗲 𝗯𝗲𝗱𝘁𝗶𝗺𝗲: When naps are consistently long, it can push the day longer and cause bedtime to fall after 8-9pm! (which can lead to early morning wakings!)⁣
⁣
𝗦𝗼...𝗵𝗼𝘄 𝗱𝗼 𝘆𝗼𝘂 𝘄𝗮𝗸𝗲 𝗮 𝘀𝗹𝗲𝗲𝗽𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗯𝗮𝗯𝘆?⁣
▪️Open the door⁣
▪️Let in a bit of light⁣
▪️Turn off the sound machine⁣
▪️Talk to baby in a low, calm voice⁣
▪️Put your hand on baby’s chest⁣
▪️Pick her up and rub her back⁣
▪️Remove the swaddle/sleep sack⁣
▪️Carry him into the well-lit living room⁣
⁣
Waking a sleepy newborn can be a bit more challenging.⁣
𝗛𝗲𝗿𝗲 𝗮𝗿𝗲 𝘀𝗼𝗺𝗲 𝘁𝗶𝗽𝘀:⁣
▪️change his diaper⁣
▪️sit her up and burp her⁣
▪️take his clothes off mid feeding⁣
▪️lay her down (away from your body)⁣
▪️rub a damp wash cloth across her face⁣
*If you are expecting or have a baby 12 weeks or younger- check out the newborn class. Link in bio! I know you’ll love this class! ❤️⁣
⁣
Want to see sample schedules showing no single nap exceeding✌🏽hours? Go to today’s stories! ⁣
⁣
So...have you ever had to wake your baby from a nap? Did others wonder why you would wake a sleeping baby? What was your response?⁣
Any other tips for how to wake little ones?⁣
